          "body": "The chapter's closing verses (7:35-38) perform two functions. First, they establish the priestly portions (wave breast and heave thigh) as permanent entitlements dating from the anointing day — mishchah, the 'anointed portion' (7:35), is the only occurrence of this noun in the entire Old Testament, marking the priestly allocation as uniquely covenantal. Second, the summary colophon (7:37-38) lists all six major sacrifices — burnt, grain, sin, guilt, ordination, and peace offerings — and attributes them in a single sentence to Yahweh's command at Mount Sinai in the Wilderness of Sinai. The repetition of 'Sinai' is emphatic: this is not a composite tradition assembled over centuries but a unified revelation delivered at a specific place to a specific man on a specific day. The entire sacrificial system — every fat portion, every blood sprinkling, every eating-window, every priestly allotment — finds its legitimacy not in human religious invention but in divine command. For the New Testament interpreter, this anchors Christ's fulfillment in real history: the One who is the asham of Isaiah 53 completes a system that was itself anchored in history from the day it was given."
